  <li id="comment-7391" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Anonymous</cite></div>
      <a href="index.html?p=1413#comment-7391"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2009-09-15T14:17:23-04:00">Tuesday, September 15, 2009 at 2:17 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Marcella Hazan taught me how to cook when I got married 20 years ago.  You haven&#39;t lived until you&#39;ve made and served at a dinner party her Baked Green Lasagne with Meat Sauce, Bolognese Style.  It takes time to make since you should make everything from scratch &#8212; the green lasagne noodles, bechamel sauce, and the bolognese meat sauce which needs to cook 3-4 hours (the meat sauce is a masterpiece in itself). But her lasagne is the most glorious dish and still my favorite after all these years.  I still remember the looks on my guests faces when they tasted it &#8212; pure love.  I&#39;ve never served a dish since, that evoked that kind of response.  Of course, her pesto recipe and alfredo recipe are unsurpassed too.  Like I said &#8212; she taught me how to cook.  I guess her cookbook, Essentials of Classic Italian Cooking is my favorite of all the cookbooks I own.</p>
    </div>

